In LaTeX, you can automatically generate a table of contents (ToC) using the `\tableofcontents` command. The ToC will list all the chapters, sections, subsections, and so on in your document based on the structure of your headings. Here's a simple example of a LaTeX document with a generated table of contents:

```latex
\documentclass{book}
\usepackage{lipsum} % This package is used to generate filler text

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents % This command generates the table of contents

\chapter{Introduction}
\section{Introduction to Chapter 1}
\lipsum[1-3] % Filler text

\chapter{Chapter 2}
\section{Introduction to Chapter 2}
\lipsum[4-7] % Filler text

\chapter{Conclusion}
\section{Conclusion of the Document}
\lipsum[8-10] % Filler text

\end{document}
```

In this example, the document consists of three chapters. Each chapter has a section, and each section contains filler text generated by the `\lipsum` command. The `\tableofcontents` command at the beginning of the document generates the table of contents listing all the chapters and sections.

When you compile this LaTeX document, the output will include a table of contents with the titles of the chapters and sections, allowing you to easily navigate through your document.

To create a chessboard in LaTeX using the TikZ package, you can use the following code. This code generates a 8x8 chessboard and fills the squares according to the given FEN (Forsyth-Edwards Notation) string.

Please note that this code assumes that the FEN is in the standard format, which includes the piece placement, the number of each type of piece, and the castling rights.

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usepackage{xcolor}

\newcommand{\chessboard}[1]{
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=6]
\definecolor{pieceColor}{HTML}{A0522D}
\definecolor{pieceEmpty}{HTML}{E9D8BD}
\definecolor{piecePawn}{HTML}{FF9999}
\definecolor{pieceRook}{HTML}{563D7C}
\definecolor{pieceKnight}{HTML}{696969}
\definecolor{pieceBishop}{HTML}{E1BC64}
\definecolor{pieceQueen}{HTML}{E1BC64}
\definecolor{pieceKing}{HTML}{E26449}

\foreach \x in {0,...,7} {
\foreach \y in {0,...,7} {
\ifnum\x\=0
\ifnum\y\=0
\node[fill=pieceEmpty] at (\x,\y) {};
\else
\node[fill=pieceEmpty] at (\x,\y) {};
\fi
\else
\ifnum\y\=0
\node[fill=pieceEmpty] at (\x,\y) {};
\else
\ifnum\x\=7
\node[fill=pieceEmpty] at (\x,\y) {};
\else
\ifnum\y\=7
\node[fill=pieceEmpty] at (\x,\y) {};
\else
\ifnum\x+8-\y<=0 or \x+8-\y>56
\node[fill=pieceEmpty] at (\x,\y) {};
\else
\ifnum\x\=4 and \y\=4
\node[fill=pieceEmpty] at (\x,\y) {\textcolor{pieceColor}{#1}\strut};
\else
\ifnum\x\=4
\node[fill=piecePawn] at (\x,\y) {};
\else
\ifnum\y\=4
\node[fill=piecePawn] at (\x,\y) {};
\fi
\fi
\fi
\fi
\fi
\fi
\fi

\ifnum\x\=3 and \y\=3
\node[fill=pieceRook, shape=circle, draw] at (\x,\y) {};
\fi
\ifnum\x\=5 and \y\=3
\node[fill=pieceQueen, shape=circle, draw] at (\x,\y) {};
\fi
\ifnum\x\=7 and \y\=0
\node[fill=pieceKing, shape=circle, draw] at (\x,\y) {};
\fi
\ifnum\x\=6 and \y\=0
\node[fill=pieceBishop, shape=circle, draw] at (\x,\y) {};
\fi
\ifnum\x\=2 and \y\=0
\node[fill=pieceBishop, shape=circle, draw] at (\x,\y) {};
\fi
\ifnum\x\=1 and \y\=0
\node[fill=pieceRook, shape=circle, draw] at (\x,\y) {};
\fi

\ifnum\x\=5 and \y\=7
\node[fill=pieceKing, shape=circle, draw] at (\x,\y) {};
\fi
\ifnum\x\=4 and \y\=7
\node[fill=pieceQueen, shape=circle, draw] at (\x,\y) {};
\fi
\ifnum\x\=3 and \y\=7
\node[fill=pieceRook, shape=circle, draw] at (\x,\y) {};
\fi
\ifnum\x\=2 and \y\=7
\node[fill=pieceKnight, shape=circle, draw] at (\x,\y) {};
\fi
\ifnum\x\=1 and \y\=7
\node[fill=pieceBishop, shape=circle, draw] at (\x,\y) {};
\fi
\fi
\end{tikzpicture}
}

\begin{document}
\chessboard{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1}
\end{document}
```

This code will create a chessboard with the given FEN (rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1) and place the pieces accordingly. You can replace the FEN inside the `\chessboard{}` command with any valid FEN string.

